message.content:
We need to “build” the current liabilities balance from the transactions that “owe money” (i.e. obligations the company has to pay) and that have not been paid at the transaction date. In our case the “Initial” transactions are simply equity/cash/asset‐type entries; none of them represent a payable. Thus the “initial” value for current liabilities is 0.00.

Then we review the transactions that are of “Purchase” type (and later also any expense payable via “Account Payable”) – here only the “Purchase” entries are relevant. For each “Purchase” we check the “payment/receipt_status” field. Only those with a status “Unpaid” remain recorded as a liability (current liability) at period end. (Note that “Interest Receivables” are usually assets and “Paid” transactions leave no balance.)

Let’s scan the purchase transactions:

1. Purchase20231231001 (20000.0) – Paid   → not a liability  
2. Purchase20231231002 (40000.0) – Paid   → not a liability  
3. Purchase20231231003 (20000.0) – Paid  
4. Purchase20231231004 (1000.0) – Paid  
5. Purchase20231231005 (20000.0) – Paid  
6. Purchase20231231006 (60000.0) – Paid  
7. Purchase20231231007 (200000.0) – Paid  
8. Purchase20231231008 (300000.0) – Paid  
9. Purchase20231231009 (1000.0) – Paid  
10. Purchase20231231010 (10000.0) – Paid  
11. Purchase20231231011 (300000.0) – Unpaid → add 300000.0  
12. Purchase20231231012 (60000.0) – Paid  
13. Purchase20231231013 (3000.0) – Paid  
14. Purchase20231231014 (2000.0) – Paid  
15. Purchase20231231015 (20000.0) – Paid  
16. Purchase20231231016 (15000.0) – Paid  
17. Purchase20231231017 (100000.0) – Paid  
18. Purchase20231231018 (100000.0) – Paid  
19. Purchase20231231019 (1000.0) – Unpaid → add 1000.0  
20. Purchase20231231020 (20000.0) – Paid  
21. Purchase20231231021 (60000.0) – Paid  
22. Purchase20231231022 (100000.0) – Paid  
23. Purchase20231231023 (15000.0) – Paid  
24. Purchase20231231024 (40000.0) – Unpaid → add 40000.0  
25. Purchase20231231025 (100000.0) – Paid  
26. Purchase20231231026 (300000.0) – Paid  
27. Purchase20231231027 (60000.0) – Paid  
28. Purchase20231231028 (5000.0) – Paid  
29. Purchase20231231029 (200000.0) – Paid  
30. Purchase20231231030 (300000.0) – Paid  
31. Purchase20231231031 (40000.0) – Unpaid → add 40000.0

Only these four purchase transactions carry an “Unpaid” (or “Account Payable”) status so that the sum is:

  300000.0 + 1000.0 + 40000.0 + 40000.0 = 381000.0

No other “Expense” transaction is shown with a payment method that would “carry over” as a payable.

Thus the current liabilities at period start are 0.00 and at the end (after all the transactions) the unpaid obligations total 381000.00.

We now present the answer in the required JSON format.

--------------------------------------------------

{
  "solution": {
    "Total Current Liabilities Initial Value": "0.00",
    "Total Current Liabilities End Value": "381000.00"
  }
}
